 <text>
  <front>
   <head>To W. P. Esq. Avondale.</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="pentameter">
     <l n="1" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">WE wish for thee, dear friend! for summer eve</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">Upon thy loveliest landscape never cast</l>
     <l n="3" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">Looks of more lingering sweetness than the last.</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">The slanting sun, reluctant to bereave</l>
     <l n="5" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">Thy woods of beauty, fondly seemed to leave</l>
     <l n="6" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">Smiles of the softest light, that slowly past</l>
     <l n="7" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">In bright succession o'er each charm thou hast</l>
     <l n="8" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">Thyself so oft admired. And we might grieve</l>
     <l n="9" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">Thine eye of taste should ever wander hence</l>
     <l n="10" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">O'er scenes less lovely than thine own; but here</l>
     <l n="11" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">Thou wilt return, and feel thy home more dear;</l>
     <l n="12" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">More dear the Muses' gentler influence,</l>
     <l n="13" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">When on the busy world, with wisdom's smile,</l>
     <l n="14" met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="10">And heart uninjured, thou hast gazed awhile.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
